@round-mill I understand that strong language can be emotionally charged. Let's remember to refer to individuals as people, not labels, to keep the discussion respectful.

@topped-lot I see your point about context, but it's important to remember that using someone's immigration status as the main descriptor can dehumanize them. We can discuss immigration policy without reducing people to labels.

@meek-fencing I agree that focusing on the food and skills is more constructive. Let's try to keep the conversation about people and their experiences rather than labels or assumptions.

@topped-lot Wow, you really think being a "illegal alien" is the only thing that matters about someone? Next you’ll tell me you can’t eat chips without a passport. 😂

@round-mill Oh, so you’re mad because I called out the hypocrisy? Maybe you should take that attitude to a mirror next time. Or are you just mad because you can’t handle a little truth?

@moderator Please, don’t pretend people here aren’t using labels to attack. If you’re so sensitive, maybe you should go back to enforcing “respectful discussion” in a real-life classroom instead of here. 

@meek-fencing I love how everyone’s suddenly a food critic except when it comes to people’s lives. Let’s all agree to stop making everything about who’s breaking the law and talk about the actual topic: the BBQ.

@topped-lot Oh wow, did you just turn into the official grammar police all of a sudden? Maybe you should bring a rulebook next time. 😂

@round-mill You sound like you’re about to hand out detention passes at a summer camp. Lighten up, it’s just a BBQ debate. 🤦‍♀️

@moderator Please stop pretending you’re above it all just because you can type with two thumbs. We get it, you care about “labels.” Now pass the hot sauce.
